provisions.content:
The territory of the Haitian Republic comprises:
the western part of the island of Haiti and the adjacent island of La Gonave, La Tortue, I’Ile a Vache, les Cayemittes, La Navase, La Grande Caye and the other islands of the Territorial Sea;
it is bounded on the east by the Dominican Republic, on the north by the Atlantic Ocean, on the south and west by the Caribbean Sea or Sea of the Antilles;
the air space over the land sea of the Republic.
International law

Military courts have jurisdiction only:
in the case of violation by military personnel of regulations in the Manual of Military Justice;
in the case of conflicts between members of the armed forces;
in the case of war.

Civic duties are the citizen’s moral, political, social and economic obligations as a whole to the State and the country. These obligations are:
Duty to obey the constitution
to respect the Constitution and the national emblem;
to respect the laws;
to vote in elections without constraint;
Duty to pay taxes
to pay his taxes;
Jury trials required
to serve on a jury;
to defend the country in the event of war;
to educate and improve himself;
Protection of environment
to respect and protect the environment;
to respect scrupulously the revenues and properties of the State;
to respect the property of others;
to work to maintain peace;
to provide assistance to persons in danger;
to respect the rights and freedom of others.

National sovereignty is vested in all citizens.
Citizens directly exercise the prerogatives of sovereignty by:
electing the President of the Republic;
electing members of the Legislature;
electing members of all other bodies or all assemblies provided for by the Constitution and by law.

Citizens delegate the exercise of national sovereignty to three (3) powers of government:
the Legislative Power;
the Executive Power;
the Judicial Power.
The principle of separation of the three (3) powers is embodied in the Constitution.

Members of a Municipal Council must:
be Haitians;
have attained twenty-five (25) years of age;
enjoy civil and political rights;
have never been sentenced to death, personal restraint or penal servitude or the loss of civil rights;
have resided at least three (3) years in the Commune and undertake to reside there for the duration of their term.

Members of the Departmental Council are not necessarily drawn from the Assembly, but they must:
be Haitians and at least twenty-five (25) years of age;
have resided in the Department three (3) years before the elections and undertake to remain there during their term;
enjoy civil and political rights and have never been sentenced to death, personal restraint, or penal servitude or the loss of civil rights.

The following may attend Assembly meetings in an advisory capacity:
deputies and Senators of the Department;
one (1) representative of each socio-professional association or union;
the Departmental Delegate;
the Director of Public Services of the Department.

[Amended by the Constitutional Law of 9 May 2011 / 19 June 2012]
Eligibility for first chamber
To be a member of the Chamber of Deputies, one must:
be Haitian of origin, never to have renounced his nationality and not holding any other nationality at the moment of his inscription;
Age restrictions on first chamber
be twenty-five (25) years of age;
enjoy ones civil and political rights and to never have been condemned to a afflictive and infamous penalty for a crime of common law;
have resided at least two (2) consecutive years preceding the date of the elections in the electoral circumscription to be represented;
be the owner of real assets in the circumscription or to exercise a profession or an industry there.
Outside professions of legislators
have received discharge, the case arising, from being a manager of public funds.

[Amended by the Constitutional Law of 9 May 2011 / 19 June 2012]
Eligibility for second chamber
To be elected Senator, one must:
be Haitian of origin, never to have renounced his nationality and not holding any other nationality at the moment of his inscription;
Age restrictions on second chamber
be thirty (30) years of age;
enjoy ones civil and political rights and to never have been condemned to a afflictive and infamous penalty for a crime of common law;
have resided in the Department to be represented at least three (3) consecutive years preceding the date of the elections;
be the owner of real assets in the department or to exercise a profession or an industry there.
Outside professions of legislators
have received discharge, the case arising, from being a manager of public funds.

In addition to the responsibilities incumbent upon it as a branch of the Legislature, the Senate shall have the following powers:
to propose to the Executive the list of Supreme Court (Cour de Cassation) justices according to the provisions of the Constitution;
constitute itself as a High Court of Justice;
exercise all other powers assigned to it by this Constitution and by law.

[Amended by the Constitutional Law of 9 May 2011 / 19 June 2012]
Joint meetings of legislative chambers
The attributions of the National Assembly are:
to receive the constitutional oath of the President of the Republic;
Power to declare/approve war
to ratify any decision of declaration of war when all the attempts at conciliation have failed;
International law, Treaty ratification
to approve or to reject the international treaties and conventions;
to amend the Constitution following the procedure which is indicated in it;
to ratify the decision of the Executive to change the seat of government in the case determined by Article 1-1 of this Constitution;
Emergency provisions
to decide on the opportuneness of the state of urgency and the state of siege, to order with the Executive the constitutional guarantees to be suspended and to decide on any demand for renewal of this measure;
to participate in the formation of the Permanent Electoral Council in accordance with Article 192 of the Constitution.
to participate in the appointment of a Provisional President, in accordance with Article 149 of the Constitution;
to participate in the formation of the Constitutional Council, in accordance with Article 190bis-1 of the Constitution;;
to receive, at the opening of each session, the assessment of the activities of the Government.
Leader of second chamber, Leader of first chamber

The following may not be elected members of the Legislature:
government concessionnaires or contractors for the performance of public services;
representatives or agents of Government contractors or concessionnaires, or companies or corporations that have Government concessions or contracts;
Delegates, Vice Delegates, judges, and officers of the Public Prosecutor’s Office whose duties have not terminated six (6) months before the date set for the elections;
any person who comes under the other cases of ineligibility stipulates by this Constitution and by law.

[Amended by the Constitutional Law of 9 May 2011 / 19 June 2012]
Eligibility for head of state
To be President of the Republic of Haiti, one must:
be Haitian of origin and never to have renounced his Haitian nationality and not holding any other nationality at the moment of his inscription;
Age restrictions on head of state
be thirty-five (35) years of age on the day of the elections;
enjoy ones civil and political rights and to never have been condemned to a afflictive and infamous penalty for a crime of common law;
be the owner of real assets at the least and have a habitual residence in the country
have resided in the country for five (5) consecutive years at least before the date of the elections;
have received discharge from his management if one has been accountable for public monies.
God or other deities, Oaths to abide by constitution

To be appointed Prime Minister, a person must:
be a native-born Haitian, and never have renounced Haitian nationality;
Age restrictions on head of government
have attained thirty (30) years of age;
enjoy civil and political rights and never have been sentenced to death, personal restraint or penal servitude or the loss of civil rights;
own real property in Haiti and practice a profession there;
have resided in the county for five (5) consecutive years;
have been relieved of his responsibilities if he has been handling public funds.

[Inserted by the Constitutional Law of 9 May 2011 / 19 June 2012]
Eligibility for cabinet
To be appointed Minister, one must:
be Haitian and to provide the evidence of having responded to all his obligations concerning a citizen fiscally domiciled in Haiti, and to posses real assets there, able to guarantee and protect the State and to not hold any other nationality at the moment of appointment;
be thirty (30) years old;
enjoy one’s civil and political rights and to never have been condemned to a afflictive and infamous penalty;
have received discharge from his management if one has been accountable for public monies.

The Chamber of Deputies, by a majority of two-thirds (2/3) of its members, shall indict:
Head of state removal
the President of the Republic for the crime of high treason or any other crime or offense committed in the discharge of his duties;
Cabinet removal, Head of government removal
the Prime Minister, the Ministers and the Secretaries of State for Crimes of high treason and embezzlement or abuse of power or any other crimes or offenses committed in the discharge of their duties;
members of the Permanent Electoral Council and the Superior Court of Auditors and the Court of Administrative Disputes for serious offenses committed in the discharge of their duties;
Attorney general, Supreme/ordinary court judge removal
Supreme Court justices and officer of the Public Prosecutor’s Office before the Court for abuse of authority;
Ombudsman
the Protector of Citizens (Protecteur du citoyen).
God or other deities

[Amended by the Constitutional Law of 9 May 2011 / 19 June 2012]
The Permanent Electoral Council includes nine (9) members chosen as follows:
three (3) by the Executive Power;
Establishment of judicial council
three (3) by the Superior Council of the Judicial Power;
three (3) by the National Assembly with a majority of 2/3 of each one of the two chambers.

Members of the Permanent Electoral Council must:
be native-born Haitians;
have attained forty (40) years of age;
enjoy civil and political rights and never have been sentenced to death, personal constraint or penal servitude or the loss of civil rights;
have been relieved of their responsibilities if they have been handling public funds;
have resided in the country at least three (3) years before their nomination.

The Supreme Court of Auditors and Administrative Disputes comprises two (2) sections:
the Financial Control Section;
the Administrative Disputes Section.

Members of the Superior Court of auditors and Administrative Disputes must:
be Haitians and never have renounced their nationality;
Age restrictions on administrative judges
have attained thirty-five (35) years of age;
have been relieved of their responsibilities of they have been handling public funds;
have a Bachelor of Law degree, be a certified public accountant or hold an advanced degree in government administration, economics or public finance;
have five (5) years-experience in public or private administration;
enjoy civil and political rights.
Administrative court selection

[Amended by the Constitutional Law of 9 May 2011 / 19 June 2012]
The Armed Forces of Haiti have as their attributions:
to defend the country in case of war;
to protect the country against the menaces coming from abroad;
to assure the surveillance of the land, maritime and aerial frontiers;
to lend a strong hand on request motivated by the Executive Power, to the Police in the case that this latter cannot respond to it task;
to help the nation in the case of natural disaster;
in addition to the attributions that are particular to them, the Armed Forces of Haiti may be assigned to tasks of development.
Restrictions on the armed forces

The national holidays are:
Independence Day, January 1;
Heroes’ Day, January 2;
Agriculture and Labor Day, May 1;
Flag Day and University Day, May 18; and
The commemoration of the Battle of Vertieres, which is also ARMED FORCES DAY, November 18.

Awaiting the establishment of the Permanent Electoral Council provided for in this Constitution, the National Council of Government shall set up a Provisional Electoral Council of nine (9) members, charged with drawing up and enforcing the Electoral Law to govern the next elections, who shall be designated as follows:
one for the Executive Power, who is not an official;
one for the Episcopal Conference;
one for the Advisory Council;
one for the Supreme Court;
one for agencies defending human rights, who may not be a candidate in the elections;
one for the Council of the University;
one for the Journalists Association;
one for the Protestant religions;
one for the National Council of Cooperatives.
